---
import ServicePage from "../layouts/ServicePage.astro";
---

<ServicePage
  title="Upper Cumberland Well Pump Service Area"
  description="Where well-pump service requests are accepted: Cookeville and Putnam County, Crossville, Livingston, Sparta and surrounding Upper Cumberland, TN communities. Coverage varies by provider."
  path="/service-area/"
  h1="Well-Pump Service Requests Across Upper Cumberland"
  crumbs={[
    { name: "Home", path: "/" },
    { name: "Service Area", path: "/service-area/" },
  ]}
  defaultService=""
  isService={false}
  relatedLinks={[
    { label: "Well Pump Repair in Cookeville", href: "/well-pump-repair-cookeville-tn/" },
    { label: "Well Pump Repair in Crossville", href: "/well-pump-repair-crossville-tn/" },
    { label: "Well Pump Repair in Livingston", href: "/well-pump-repair-livingston-tn/" },
    { label: "How Referrals Work", href: "/how-referrals-work/" },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Upper Cumberland Well Pump accepts service requests from across the Upper Cumberland region
    of Tennessee. The map and list below show where requests are routed — with an honest note on
    each tier, because <strong>actual coverage varies by provider, service type, property access,
    licensing, distance and scheduling.</strong> There is no office pin on this map because there
    is no office: this is an online referral resource.
  </p>

  <img
    src="/images/map-upper-cumberland.svg"
    alt="Illustrated map of the Upper Cumberland region showing Putnam, Cumberland, Overton, White and DeKalb counties"
    width="760"
    height="560"
    loading="lazy"
    style="margin-block: 1.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--gray-border); border-radius: 10px;"
  />

  <h2>Primary Market — Cookeville &amp; Putnam County</h2>
  <p>
    Cookeville is the hub of the region and of this service: the primary content and
    lead-generation focus for pump repair, urgent no-water requests, replacement, pressure tanks
    and related water-well services. Requests from Algood, Baxter, Monterey and rural Putnam
    County roads are submitted through the same
    <a href="/well-pump-repair-cookeville-tn/">Cookeville well pump repair page</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Secondary Markets</h2>
  <h3>Crossville &amp; Cumberland County</h3>
  <p>
    Plateau communities including Fairfield Glade, Lake Tansi, Crab Orchard and Pleasant Hill.
    Cumberland County has its own request page:
    <a href="/well-pump-repair-crossville-tn/">Well Pump Repair in Crossville</a>.
  </p>
  <h3>Livingston &amp; Overton County</h3>
  <p>
    Livingston, Rickman, Alpine, Hilham, Monroe and the county's rural farm properties. See
    <a href="/well-pump-repair-livingston-tn/">Well Pump Repair in Livingston</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="sparta">Supporting Coverage</h2>
  <h3>Sparta &amp; White County</h3>
  <p>
    Requests from Sparta, Doyle, Quebeck and rural White County are accepted through the standard
    <a href="/request-service/">request form</a> — enter "Sparta" or "White County" in the
    city/county field. Provider coverage for a specific White County address is confirmed during
    routing.
  </p>
  <h3>Smithville &amp; DeKalb County</h3>
  <p>
    DeKalb County requests are accepted <strong>subject to verified provider coverage</strong> —
    routing depends on whether a provider serving that direction can take the request. Submitting
    costs nothing and gets you an honest answer either way.
  </p>
  <h3>Nearby Rural Communities</h3>
  <p>
    Jackson, Fentress and other neighboring Upper Cumberland counties fall outside the core
    focus, but rural requests from adjacent areas are welcome and routed where a provider's
    range allows.
  </p>

  <h2>How Coverage Actually Gets Confirmed</h2>
  <p>
    A request is reviewed against the providers who serve your direction, service type and
    property situation — a drilling rig ranges differently than a repair truck, and a gated farm
    two counties out is a different trip than a subdivision address. That is why this page makes
    no blanket promises. The <a href="/how-referrals-work/">how referrals work page</a> walks
    through the full process step by step.
  </p>
</ServicePage>
